Obama and Cuban President Raul Castro spoke by phone on Wednesday for only the second time in 50 years . 
  The two presidents are attending the seventh Summit of the Americas in Panama this weekend . 
  It will be the first time in more than 50 years that leaders from the previously estranged countries will have had a lengthy in-person exchange . 
  Obama and Castro are expected to have a 'discussion' at the summit . 
  They spoke on the phone Wednesday ahead of an anticipated 'interaction' on Friday . 
  Secretary of State John Kerry and Cuban Foreign Minister Bruno Rodriguez held talks in Panama City on Thursday . 
 